rows.title: If You Value Freedom
rows.titleText: There currently exists a government actively working to restrict the freedom of its citizens. They are curtailing freedom of expression through cracking down on protests, restricting independent journalism, and arresting individuals who criticize the government or express views that the government disagrees with, going so far as to break their own laws in their pursuit of silencing freedom of speech. That government is also detaining and deporting individuals, even in the absence of a crime being committed or charges being filed, sometimes for their speech critical of the government, sometimes for no given reason at all. And when instructed to halt the deportations and give due process to the deportees, the government flagrantly and gleefully defies the courts. If I asked you how you would describe such a government, it would probably be something along the lines of “authoritarian,” “illiberal,” or maybe even “dystopian.” And if I asked you what country was perpetuating such gross violations of freedom, I would expect to hear someplace like China, Russia, or perhaps North Korea. But what if I told you that all of this is happening under the self proclaimed party of individual freedom, in a country where one of the three core values is liberty?

rows.title: The Party of "Freedom"
rows.titleText: The American right-wing has referred to itself as many things, such as the party of small government, the party of law and order, and the party of individual freedom. But if you truly value freedom, you should not support the right-wing, and here's why:

objects.title: Freedom of Expression
objects.text: This button opens the section on freedom of expression when clicked.

objects.title: Freedom Under the Law
objects.text: This button opens the section on freedom regarding the legal system when clicked.

rows.title: Freedom of Expression
rows.titleText: Freedom of Expression is one of the most crucial aspects of a functional democracy. For voters to make informed choices they need access to unbiased and accurate information regarding the government and influential figures. And citizens need to be able to speak without fear of censorship and organize without fear of retaliation, even if they are saying things that are critical of the government. But the Trump administration and by extension, the modern right-wing, has been actively undermining freedom of expression through detaining protestors, deporting critics, throttling the access of independent journalists, and holding educational institution's funds hostage.

objects.title: Mahmoud Khalil
objects.text: Mahmoud Khalil is a graduate student at Columbia University and played a prominent role in organizing protests against Israel's actions in Gaza. On March 8th immigration agents arrested him under orders to revoke his student visa. Upon being informed by his attorney that he was in the United States as a permanent resident with a green card the agent stated that they were revoking that instead. Khalil has not been charged with any crime and is still being detained.

objects.title: Rumeysa Ozturk
objects.text: Rumeysa Ozturk was detained on March 25th and had her visa revoked. In revoking her visa, the State Department cited a 2024 op-ed she co-authored in the student newspaper that criticized the university's response to the Israel-Hamas war. Ozturk was moved to a Louisiana ICE processing center in violation of a court order stating that Ozturk was not to be moved outside the District of Massachusetts without 48 hours advance notice.

objects.title: Press Access
objects.text: The Trump administration has revoked press access and to AP news for refusing to refer to the Gulf of Mexico as the Gulf of America. AP news has also been kicked off of Air Force One. The Trump Administration has also announced that it is seizing control of the press pool covering President Trump, becoming the first administration in decades to do so. Beyond just banning AP news and Reuters from the pool, the administration has worked to increase access for partisan figures sympathetic to the administration, such as Sage Steele and Brian Glenn.

objects.title: Educational Institutions
objects.text: The Trump administration has threatened multiple higher education institutions by threatening and in some cases actually pausing funding to those institutions for a variety of reasons. The administration issued a list of demands necessary for a "continued financial relationship" including a ban on face masks, limitations on campus protests, a review of academic departments' biases, leadership reforms, admission policy changes, and stopping the university's recognition of certain student organizations. Hours after the Harvard president, Alan Gerber, refused to comply, the administration announced it froze over $2.2 billion dollars in grants and $60 million in contracts to the university. And this is only one of many universities where this is happening.

rows.title: Freedom of Expression
rows.titleText: There have been a variety of reasons given and justifications for the limitations on freedom of speech, ranging from that it was for the good of society that someone criticizing the government was deported, to that the speech was false, and even to that the information was "improper ideology." But according to John Stuart Mill and other philosophers, these aren't valid reasons to limit speech and are instead infringements on freedom. According to Mill it's good to allow true beliefs, and it's true to allow false beliefs.

objects.title: Truth
objects.text: The Trump administration is actively attempting to distort the indisputable truth in certain fields by scrubbing mention and language of them from government websites. The best example of this would be the Trump administrations claim that there are only two biological sexes. This claim is objectively false and one has to look no further than the variety of intersex conditions such as de la Chapelle syndrome, XYY syndrome, androgen insensitivity syndrome, and a variety of others. By attempting to suppress the truth, the Trump administration is actively harming both individuals and society, through attempting to erase the medical reality of these conditions, halting scientific and medical progress, and fomenting arrogance and intolerance.

objects.title: Falsity
objects.text: The Trump admin has also claimed that various things are false, including the concept of gender identity, that the Gulf of Mexico is the proper name for the Gulf of Mexico, and that there was and still is systematic racism and sexism. Despite the Trump admin having little evidence for these claims and overwhelming evidence to the contrary, for the sake of the argument we will hold that the Trump admin is correct and the aforementioned things are false. Even if these things were false, the Trump admin's attempted suppression of them and retaliation against those who claim otherwise is a violation of freedom. Although it may seem counterintuitive, when falsity is censored it harms individuals and society. The reason this is the case is because even if someone was right, how would they know? Until you you've considered the opposing views and argued against them one can't know that they are correct. Being confronted with with different ideas strengthens your views. Mill described it aptly when he said "complete liberty of contradicting and disproving our opinion is the very condition which justifies us in assuming its truth".

objects.title: Moral Standards
objects.text: The Trump admin has also claimed that gender identify and other related concepts are immoral. Even ignoring the veracity or lack thereof, according to Mill this is an illegitimate reason to suppress freedom of speech as it is not preventing harms from others or protecting freedom.

objects.title: Benefit of Society
objects.text: There are those that claim that the deportations of individuals who criticize the government or who support views that the government disagrees with are for the benefit of society. But much like with Moral Standards, the claims that the deportation of individuals like Mahmoud Khalil or Rumeysa Ozturk was for the benefit of society are also illegitimate. They neither prevent harm from others or protect freedom, instead infringing upon freedom.

rows.title: Freedom Under the Law
rows.titleText: But even beyond the right wing's violations of freedom of expression, they have also infringed upon individuals' physical freedoms in ways that dwarf any potential freedom infringements by the left-wing.

objects.title: Abrego Garcia
objects.text: In 2019 Abrego Garcia was granted protection from removal to El Salvador by an immigration judge and Garcia gained a legal work permit issued by the Department of Homeland Security. On 3/12/2025 Garcia was arrested in Baltimore after working a shift as a sheet metal apprentice. He was then sent to the the Terrorism Confinement Center in El Salvador, or CECOT, without a trial or a chance  to defend himself in a court. Garcia has never been charged or convicted with a crime and had followed all the stipulations of his protected status. Despite the Trump administration acknowledging that Garcia was deported without due process and sent to El Salvador due to an "administrative error". Despite the Supreme Court upholding a ruling from a lower court that the administration must facilitate Garcia's release from custody in El Salvador, the administration has claimed that there is nothing it can do to retrieve him,  despite having sent the Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem to the prison and having previously retrieved wrongly incarcerated individuals. In response to the government's argument, Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor wrote that "The Government’s argument, moreover, implies that it could deport and incarcerate any person, including U. S. citizens, without legal consequence, so long as it does so before a court can intervene."

objects.title: Defiance of Court Orders
objects.text: The Trump administration has defied a variety of court orders, including an order to halt deportations under the Alien Enemies Act. At the time the order was given two planes headed to El Salvador containing deportees from a Texas detention facilities were in the air, and a third plane took off after the hearing and the order being formally published. The next morning, El Salvador's President Nayib Bukele tweeted "Oopsie...too late" above an article referencing the order and announced that over 200 deportees had arrived in his country, The White House communications director, Steven Cheung, reposted Bukele's post with an admiring GIF.

rows.title: Freedom Under the Law
rows.titleText: The right-wing has eroded freedom and the principles underpinning liberal democracy by ignoring due process and the destruction of critical checks and balances.

objects.title: Due Process
objects.text: Due process is a critically important part of any liberal democracy. It is the fundamental principle that all legal matters must be resolved in accordance with the established rules, laws, and regulations. But there are disagreements over who gets due process. There are those who argue that some people shouldn't get due process, that they do not deserve it. One of the most common examples of this is the argument that immigrants should be exempt from receiving due process because of the time required to give all of them a trial, with Trump claiming that "[w]e cannot give everyone a trial, because to do so would take, without exaggeration, 200 years." This may seem reasonable to some at first glance, but it raises a multitude issues. Without due process, there are no guardrails to prevent the government from causing harm in a way that offers no recourse. In the case of Abrego Garcia, he had protection from removal to El Salvador because he was at serious risk of retaliatory killings by El Salvadoran gangs. There is no way to undo the potential harm done if it comes to pass, which is one of the reasons why due process is so important. But even beyond that, due process guarantees that people get fair trials and have a chance to prove that they are not guilty of what they are accused of, which is why if only some people get due process, then nobody really has due process. If the government has the ability to to imprison and punish individuals without going through the courts, combined with the ability to move them beyond the reach of the courts, the only thing preventing it from exercising that power on anyone it wants is the will to do so.

objects.title: Checks and Balances
objects.text: Checks and balances are another necessary component of liberal democracy. They act to keep the power of the government in check and to prevent it from violating its own laws. Having an independent judiciary that is bound under a constitution is important because it is supposed to ensure that the government cannot act in ways that violate that constitution. Historically, the executive branch has complied with the decisions of the courts despite the latter lacking a significant mechanism to enforce those decisions. But the Trump administration has demonstrated that it can and will gleefully disregard the courts, with the previously mentioned White House communications director's admiring response to El Salvador's President's tweet serving as proof. And if you need further proof, in response to being asked if he needed to uphold the constitution, Trump said "I don't know...." Based on the right-wing's willingness and ability to disregard the checks and balances in place and the constitution itself, there is nothing stopping them from violating the freedom of any individual, in any way they please, at any time, for any reason.

rows.title: In Conclusion
rows.titleText: In conclusion, based on the Trump administration's, and by extension, the modern right-wing's actions in attempting to suppress freedom of speech  through the arrest and deportation of individuals for expressing their speech, the limitation of press access for independent reporting groups, the holding of funds hostage for educational institutions, the active distortion and suppression of biological factors that don't fit their narrative, the attempted censorship and removal of things they claim to be false, often without basis, and the illegitimate attempts to censor speech based on subjective moral standards or for perceived benefit of society, the right-wing has demonstrated that it is at best willing to turn a blind eye towards infringements on free speech, and at worst, an active opponent of it. And through their actions in stripping away due process, gleeful defiance of court orders, sidestepping of checks and balances, and Trump's open admission that he is unsure of whether he needs to obey the constitution, the right-wing has demonstrated that they are opponent of freedom and the core principles underpinning liberal democracy. Taking all of this into account, if your most important political value is freedom, you should not support the right-wing

On both rows and choices Requirements can be placed, which will block a row from being viewed, or make the player unable to select a choice, depending on either Point-types or the Ids of other choices. Point-types can be made in Features then Manage Points. Hovering over buttons will explain what they do. The Design of the project can be changed in 'Modify Design' at the side navigation bar, and private styling for each row can be turned on in the rows Settings. Default text like this can be turned off in Features -> Manage Defaults.
defaultChoiceText: This is a Choice, and inside of it, you can place images and text. Scores can be added to it, and have Point-types attached. Addons can be added underneath the image and text. In the Functions at the bottom of the choice, there is an array of different things that can be done. Default text like this can be turned off in Features then Manage Defaults.
